I certainly don't deny that there are powerful corporations/organizations in the fossil fuels business such as OPEC who shriek at the thought of nuclear power or other energy sources taking a major foothold and thus probably fund anti-nuclear groups as a defensive measure.  When I'm going postal about how anti-nuclear activists blame all environmental problems on greedy corporations I'm not so much defending the corporations as I'm angry about how these activists go out of their way to make nuclear technology unprofitable than have the hypocrisy to say its all someone else's fault that we don't have clean air to breathe and I just generally hate their luddite stances toward everything that has promise.  It would be interesting to examine the books of some of these environmental organizations to see who their major sponsors are.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 418<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/16/02 2:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=102.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: EU Commissioner Speaks in favour of Nuclear Power.</span><hr size=1> I should also add that I don't like how these more radical groups use their environmental concerns to support their political agendas which are decidedly anti-free enterprise and totalitarian.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicrod>atomicrod</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/16/02 8:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=102.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: EU Commissioner Speaks in favour of Nuclear Power.</span><hr size=1> The words of ignorant people do not concern me very much. It is the carefully chosen words of knowledgeable people that I worry about.<br>
<br>
For example, if you do some library mining, you can find some interesting information about E. F. Schumacher, the author of &quot;Small is Beautiful&quot;, a book ranks about equal to Rachel Carson's &quot;Silent Spring&quot; in the lexicon of &quot;environmentalism&quot;.<br>
<br>
What few people seem to know is that Schumacher was a career employee of Britain's National Coal Board. During the time he worked there, coal was continually losing market share to large, central station electricity produced by burning oil, gas, or by fission. The coal market that was disappearing was that illustrated most clearly when Julia Andrews and Dick Van Dyke dance with sooty faces on the roof under a black cloud while singing the song with the chorus of &quot;Chim, chininey, chim, chiminey, chim, chim cheroo&quot;. (Sorry if you have not seen &quot;Mary Poppins&quot;, I have spent many happy hours with my daughters watching Disney flicks.) <br>
<br>
No longer were people burning coal at home in the innumerable small, distributed furnaces that turned both lungs and buildings black. Instead, they were installing electric heaters supplied from those big, distant plants that burned a different fuel imported from a distant land.<br>
<br>
That is the market shift that Schumacher and the National Coal Board wanted to slow and perhaps even reverse. Hiding that message as &quot;environmentalism&quot; is what is known as semantics, spinning, or marketing. <br>
<br>
Rod Adams<br>
